South African former World Cup of Golf winner Wayne Westner, 55, died in Pennington, in KwaZulu-Natal on Wednesday. Westner won the World Cup of Golf with compatriot Ernie Els in 1996. The promising player had his career cut short through injury in 1998, having won twice on the European Tour. In total, Westner won 14 times in his professional career, including two triumphs in the SA Open in 1988 and 1991. Four-time Major winner Els led the tributes on social media. Sad day, our friend Wayne Westner passed today. Great memories thank you my friend, tweeted Els. South African-born professional and Olympic Gold medalist in the golf event at Rio 2016 Justin Rose tweeted: So sad. A true gentleman of the game. Police spokesman Lieutenant Thulani Zwane said that police had received a call to attend to an incident on an estate in Pennington. On arrival police found the body of Westner, who had sustained a gunshot wound to the head. A 9mm pistol was recovered. Zwane said that an inquest docket had been opened. One source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that Westner was in the process of relocating to Gauteng. This could not immediately be confirmed. African News Agency (ANA)